# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: capacitor-discharge-ignition
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] *Right* - The left magneto p-lead is grounded, and the right is open.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the left magneto and enables the right magneto only.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] *Left* - The right magneto p-lead is grounded, and the left is open.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the right magneto and enables the left magneto only.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] *Both* - This is the normal operating configuration, both p-leads are open, enabling both magnetos.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] *Start* - The pinion gear on the starter motor is engaged with the flywheel and the starter motor runs to turn the engine over.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] In most cases, only the left magneto is active (the right p-lead is grounded) due to timing differences between the magnetos at low RPMs.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] In an aircraft with a **fixed-pitch propeller**, there is no direct control over the propeller rotational speed, which depends on the airspeed and loading.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] Therefore, the pilot has to pay attention to the RPM indicator and adjust the throttle/power lever in order to maintain the desired constant speed of the propeller.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] For example, when the airspeed reduces and the loading increases (e.g., in a climb), RPM will decrease and the pilot has to increase the throttle/power.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] When the airspeed increases and the loading decreases (e.g., in a dive), the RPM will increase and the pilot has to decrease the throttle/power in order to prevent RPM from exceeding the operational limits and damaging the motor.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] Restricting the volume of cooling airflow too much.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] Insufficient delivery of lubricating oil to the engine's moving parts.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Many variations of **aircraft engine starting** have been used since the Wright brothers made their first powered flight in 1903.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The methods used have been designed for weight saving, simplicity of operation and reliability.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Early piston engines were started by hand.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Geared hand starting, electrical and cartridge-operated systems for larger engines were developed between the First and Second World Wars.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Gas turbine aircraft engines such as turbojets, turboshafts and turbofans often use air/pneumatic starting, with the use of *bleed air* from built-in auxiliary power units (APUs) or external air compressors now seen as a common starting method.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Often only one engine needs be started using the APU (or remote compressor).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] After the first engine is started using APU bleed air, *cross-bleed air* from the running engine can be used to start the remaining engine(s).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Hand starting of aircraft piston engines by swinging the propeller is the oldest and simplest method, the absence of any onboard starting system giving an appreciable weight saving.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Positioning of the propeller relative to the crankshaft is arranged such that the engine pistons pass through top dead centre during the swinging stroke.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] As the ignition system is normally arranged to produce sparks before top dead centre there is a risk of the engine kicking back during hand starting.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] To avoid this problem one of the two magnetos used in a typical aero engine ignition system is fitted with an 'impulse coupling', a spring-loaded device which delays the spark until top dead centre and which also increases the rotational speed of the magneto to produce a stronger spark.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] When the engine fires, the impulse coupling no longer operates and the second magneto is switched on.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Note that this is different from the manual "turning over" of a radial piston engine, which is done to release oil that has become trapped in the lower cylinders prior to starting to avoid engine damage.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The two appear similar, but while hand starting involves a sharp, strong "yank" on the prop to start the engine, turning over is simply done by turning the prop through a certain set amount.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Accidents have occurred during lone pilot hand starting, whether due to high throttle settings, brakes not having been applied, or wheel chocks not being used, all resulting in the aircraft moving off without the pilot at the controls.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The Hucks starter (invented by Bentfield Hucks during WWI) is a mechanical replacement for the ground crew.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Based on a vehicle chassis the device uses a clutch driven shaft to turn the propeller, disengaging as the engine starts.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] A Hucks starter is used regularly at the Shuttleworth Collection for starting period aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Self-sustaining motor gliders (often known as 'turbos') are fitted with small two-stroke engines with no starting system, for ground testing a cord is wrapped around the propeller boss and pulled rapidly in conjunction with operating decompressor valves.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] These engines are started in flight by operating the decompressor and increasing airspeed to windmill the propeller.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Early variants of the Slingsby Falke motor glider use a cockpit mounted pull start system.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Aircraft began to be equipped with electrical systems around 1930, powered by a battery and small wind-driven generator.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The systems were initially not powerful enough to drive starter motors.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Introduction of engine-driven generators solved the problem.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Introduction of electric starter motors for aero engines increased convenience at the expense of extra weight and complexity.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] They were a necessity for flying boats with high mounted, inaccessible engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Powered by an onboard battery, ground electrical supply or both, the starter is operated by a key or switch in the cockpit.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The key system usually facilitates switching of the magnetos.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] In cold ambient conditions the friction caused by viscous engine oil causes a high load on the starting system.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Another problem is the reluctance of the fuel to vaporise and combust at low temperatures.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Oil dilution systems were developed (mixing fuel with the engine oil), and engine pre-heaters were used (including lighting fires under the engine).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The Ki-Gass priming pump system was used to assist starting of British engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Aircraft fitted with variable-pitch propellers or constant speed propellers are started in fine pitch to reduce air loads and current in the starter motor circuit.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Many light aircraft are fitted with a 'starter engaged' warning light in the cockpit, a mandatory airworthiness requirement to guard against the risk of the starter motor failing to disengage from the engine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The Coffman starter was an explosive cartridge operated device, the burning gases either operating directly in the cylinders to rotate the engine or operating through a geared drive.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] First introduced on the Junkers Jumo 205 diesel engine in 1936 the Coffman starter was not widely used by civil operators due to the expense of the cartridges.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] In 1920 Roy Fedden designed a piston engine gas starting system, used on the Bristol Jupiter engine in 1922.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] A system used in early Rolls-Royce Kestrel engines ducted high-pressure air from a ground unit through a camshaft driven distributor to the cylinders via non-return valves, the system had disadvantages only overcome by conversion to electric starting.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] When a piston engine needs to be started in flight the electric starter motor can be used.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] This is a normal procedure for motor gliders that have been soaring with the engine turned off.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] During aerobatics with earlier aircraft types it was not uncommon for the engine to cut during manoeuvres due to carburettor design.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] With no electric starter installed, engines can be restarted by diving the aircraft to increase airspeed and the rotation speed of the 'windmilling' propeller.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] An aero engine inertia starter uses a pre-rotated flywheel to transfer kinetic energy to the crankshaft, normally through reduction gears and a clutch to prevent over-torque conditions.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Three variations have been used, hand driven, electrically driven and a combination of both.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] When the flywheel is fully energised either a manual cable is pulled or a solenoid is used to engage the starter.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Starting of a gas turbine engine requires rotation of the compressor to a speed that provides sufficient pressurised air to the combustion chambers.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The starting system has to overcome inertia of the compressor and friction loads, the system remains in operation after combustion starts and is disengaged once the engine has reached self-idling speed.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Two types of electrical starter motor can be used, direct-cranking (to disengage as internal combustion engines) and starter-generator system (permanently engaged).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Small gas turbine engines, particularly turboshaft engines used in helicopters and cruise missile turbojets can be started by a geared hydraulic motor using oil pressure from a ground supply.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] With air-start systems, gas turbine engine compressor spools are rotated by the action of a large volume of compressed air acting directly on the compressor blades or driving the engine through a small, geared turbine motor.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] These motors can weigh up to 75% less than an equivalent electrical system.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The compressed air can be supplied from an on-board auxiliary power unit (APU), a portable gas generator used by ground crew or by cross feeding bleed air from a running engine in the case of multi-engined aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The Turbomeca Palouste gas generator was used to start the Spey engines of the Blackburn Buccaneer.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The de Havilland Sea Vixen was equipped with its own Palouste in a removable underwing container to facilitate starting when away from base.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Other military aircraft types using ground supplied compressed air for starting include the Lockheed F-104 Starfighter and variants of the F-4 Phantom using the General Electric J79 turbojet engine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Versions of the Rolls-Royce Avon turbojet engine used a geared turbine starter motor that burned isopropyl nitrate as the fuel.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] In military service this monofuel had the NATO designation of S-746 AVPIN.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] For starting a measured amount of fuel was introduced to the starter combustion chamber then ignited electrically, the hot gases spinning the turbine at high revolutions with the exhaust exiting overboard.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Similar in operating principle to the piston engine Coffman starter, an explosive cartridge drives a small turbine engine which is connected by gears to the compressor shaft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Developed for short-haul airliners, most civil and military aircraft requiring self-contained starting systems these units are known by various names including Auxiliary Power Unit (APU), Jet Fuel Starter (JFS), Air Start Unit (ASU) or Gas Turbine Compressor (GTC).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Comprising a small gas turbine which is electrically started, these devices provide compressed bleed air for engine starting and often also provide electrical and hydraulic power for ground operations without the need to run the main engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Two small petrol/oil mix tanks were fitted in the annular intake.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird used two Buick Nailheads as starter motors, which were mounted on an AG-330 Start Kart trolley, later with Chevrolet big-block 454-cubic-inch (7.44 L) V8 engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Gas turbine engines can be shut down in flight, intentionally by the crew to save fuel or during a flight test or unintentionally due to fuel starvation or flameout after a compressor stall.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Sufficient airspeed is used to 'windmill' the compressor then fuel and ignition are switched on, an on-board auxiliary power unit may be used at high altitudes where the air density is lower.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] During zoom climb operations of the Lockheed NF-104A the jet engine was shut down on climbing through 85,000 ft (26,000 m) and was started using the windmill method on descent through denser air.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Pulse jet engines are uncommon aircraft powerplants.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] However, the Argus As 014 used to power the V-1 flying bomb and Fieseler Fi 103R Reichenberg was a notable exception.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Once the engine started and the temperature rose to the minimum operating level, the external air hose and connectors were removed, and the resonant design of the tailpipe kept the pulse jet firing.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Each cycle or pulse of the engine began with the shutters open; fuel was injected behind them and ignited, and the resulting expansion of gases forced the shutters closed.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] As the pressure in the engine dropped following combustion, the shutters reopened and the cycle was repeated, roughly 40 to 45 times per second.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The electrical ignition system was used only to start the engine; heating of the tailpipe skin maintained combustion.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] An **aircraft fuel system** allows the crew to pump, manage, and deliver aviation fuel to the propulsion system and auxiliary power unit (APU) of an aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Fuel systems differ greatly due to different performance of the aircraft in which they are installed.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] A single-engine piston aircraft has a simple fuel system, while a tanker (such as the KC-135) not only manages its own fuel but can also provide fuel to other aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Fuel is piped through fuel lines to a fuel control valve (usually known as the fuel selector).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] The first function is to act as a fuel shut-off valve.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] This is required to provide the crew with a means to prevent fuel reaching the engine in case of an engine fire.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] The second function is to allow the pilot to choose which tank feeds the engine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Many aircraft have the left tank and right tank selections available to the pilot.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Some Cessna airplanes feed only from both tanks; and many have the option to feed from left, right, or both tanks.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] The reason to have left only and right only options is to allow pilots to balance fuel load to reduce the banking moment.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] In some aircraft, the shut-off function is a different valve located after the fuel selector valve.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Typically, after the selector valve—situated at a low point in the fuel run—there is a gascolator — a fuel filter that can be opened on the ground and drained of fuel impurities denser than petroleum, mainly water and sediment.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Other drainage points are in each tank (often more than one contaminant collection sump per tank) and at the injection pump.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Each tank is vented (or pressurised) to allow air into the tank to take the place of burned fuel; otherwise, the tank would be in negative pressure which would result in engine fuel starvation.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] A vent also allows for changes in atmospheric pressure and temperature.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] The fuel level indication system in the simplest form is a transparent window on the tank side and in its usual application a float-driven potentiometer installed in the tank.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] After the TWA Flight 800 disaster, a revision was made to aircraft fuel systems to address the potential explosion hazard of electrical components located in the fuel tank.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Single-engine piston aircraft fuel level systems moved to utilize float level gauges from the CNG and LPG industries which had the float drive a magnetic coupling and relocated the potentiometer outside the fuel tank.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Some single-engine aircraft use capacitive probes in the fuel tanks.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] As fuel is burned, more air enters the tank and the capacitance decreases; this is read by a computer and the fuel amount is calculated and displayed to the pilots.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Recent advances in magnetoresistive technology have evolved new fuel level sensors for general aviation applications.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] This system is not affected by any additive or fuel combination to replace 100LL for piston-powered aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Single-engine light aircraft fuel tanks are usually in the wings, but some aircraft have a small "header tank" between the normal fuel tank and the engine, to facilitate reliable fuel flow to the engine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] On many small or very old single-engine aircraft, header tanks (and even main tanks) are often mounted above and/or immediately behind the engine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] A few (particularly ultralight aircraft) have them in the fuselage or on the airframe behind the pilot and/or passenger(s).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Adding tanks and engines increases the complexity of the fuel system and its management.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] All of the considerations made for the twin piston are applicable to turbine fuel systems.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Additional consideration apply because of the higher altitudes, different fuel, lower temperatures, and longer flights.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] To avoid water condensation or the fuel itself solidifying at low temperatures (−55 °C), fuel tanks have thermometers and heating systems.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Many are pressurized with engine bleed air to keep moist air out and ensure positive pressure feed to the pumps.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] In larger aircraft, fuel tanks also are in the fuselage and their load affects the center of gravity of the aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] This imposes limitations on the amount of fuel carried and the order in which fuel must be used.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Turbine engines burn fuel faster than reciprocating engines do.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Because fuel needs to be injected in to a combustor, the injection system of a turbine aircraft must provide fuel at higher pressure and flow compared to that for a piston engine aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] The refueling system of larger aircraft includes a single positive pressure refueling point from which all tanks can be fueled.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] How much and to which tanks fuel is fed during refueling operations is determined by the controls in the refueling panel, usually installed nearby and accessible to ground crews.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] External tanks are used to extend the range of an aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Drop tanks are used by combat aircraft that need to discard them after use for performance reasons.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] A fuel pump is required to transfer fuel from a tip tank to a main tank.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] An **aircraft** is a vehicle that can fly by gaining support from the air.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] It counters the force of gravity by using either static lift or the dynamic lift of an airfoil, or, in a few cases, direct downward thrust from its engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Common examples of aircraft include airplanes, drones, rotorcraft (including helicopters), airships (including blimps), gliders, paramotors, and hot air balloons.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Part 1 (Definitions and Abbreviations) of Subchapter A of Chapter I of Title 14 of the U.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Code of Federal Regulations states that *aircraft* "means a device that is used or intended to be used for flight in the air".
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The human activity that surrounds aircraft is called *aviation*.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The science of aviation includes the designing and building of aircraft, which is called *aeronautics*. a *crewed* aircraft is flown by an onboard pilot, whereas an unmanned aerial vehicle may be remotely controlled or *autonomous*, controlled by onboard computers.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Aircraft may be classified by different criteria, such as lift type, propulsion (if any), usage and others.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The history of aviation spans over two millennia, from the earliest innovations like kites and attempts at tower jumping to supersonic and hypersonic flight in powered, heavier-than-air jet aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Kite flying in China, dating back several hundred years BC, is considered the earliest example of man-made flight.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In the 15th century, Leonardo da Vinci created flying machine designs incorporating aeronautical concepts, but they were unworkable due to the limitations of contemporary knowledge.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In the late 18th century, the Montgolfier brothers invented the hot-air balloon which soon led to manned flights.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] At almost the same time, the discovery of hydrogen gas led to the invention of the hydrogen balloon.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Various theories in mechanics by physicists during the same period, such as fluid dynamics and Newton's laws of motion, led to the development of modern aerodynamics; most notably by Sir George Cayley.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Balloons, both free-flying and tethered, began to be used for military purposes from the end of the 18th century, with France establishing balloon companies during the French Revolution.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In the 19th century, especially the second half, experiments with gliders provided the basis for learning the dynamics of winged aircraft; most notably by Cayley, Otto Lilienthal, and Octave Chanute.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] By the early 20th century, advances in engine technology and aerodynamics made controlled, powered, manned heavier-than-air flight possible for the first time.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In 1903, following their pioneering research and experiments with wing design and aircraft control, the Wright brothers successfully incorporated all of the required elements to create and fly the first airplane.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In 1906 Charles Frederick Page was granted the first U.S. patent for an aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The basic configuration with its characteristic cruciform tail was established by 1909, followed by rapid design and performance improvements aided by the development of more powerful engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The first vessels of the air were the rigid steerable balloons pioneered by Ferdinand von Zeppelin that became synonymous with airships and dominated long-distance flight until the 1930s, when large flying boats became popular for trans-oceanic routes.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] After World War II, the flying boats were in turn replaced by airplanes operating from land, made far more capable first by improved propeller engines, then by jet engines, which revolutionized both civilian air travel and military aviation.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In the latter half of the 20th century, the development of digital electronics led to major advances in flight instrumentation and "fly-by-wire" systems.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The 21st century has seen the widespread use of pilotless drones for military, commercial, and recreational purposes.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] With computerized controls, inherently unstable aircraft designs, such as flying wings, have also become practical.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Lighter-than-air aircraft or *aerostats* use buoyancy to float in the air in much the same way that ships float on the water.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] They are characterized by one or more large cells or canopies, filled with a lifting gas such as helium, hydrogen or hot air, which is less dense than the surrounding air.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Other gases lighter than air also theoretically work; however, such gases also need to be safe for human use (non-flammable, non-toxic).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Small hot-air balloons, called sky lanterns, were first invented in ancient China prior to the 3rd century BC and used primarily in cultural celebrations, although they also had military purposes.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] They, along with kites, were two forms of unmanned aircraft that originated from China.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Kites were also used in the military, but unlike sky lanterns, their flight is caused by the differences in air pressure beneath and above the kite.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] A balloon was originally any aerostat, while the term airship was used for large, powered aircraft designs—usually fixed-wing.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In 1919, Frederick Handley Page was reported as referring to "ships of the air," with smaller passenger types as "Air yachts." In the 1930s, large intercontinental flying boats were also sometimes referred to as "ships of the air" or "flying-ships".
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Lighter-than-air aircraft don't typically require a pilot's license in the United States.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In most countries in Europe, standards for flying Lighter-than-air aircraft tend to be stricter compared to the United States.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Heavier-than-air aircraft or *aerodynes* are denser than air and thus must find some way to obtain enough lift that can overcome the aircraft's weight.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] There are two ways to produce dynamic upthrust—aerodynamic lift by having air flowing past an aerofoil (such dynamic interaction of aerofoils with air is the origin of the term "aerodyne"), or powered lift in the form of reactional lift from downward engine thrust.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Aerodynamic lift involving wings is the most common, and can be achieved via two methods.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Fixed-wing aircraft (airplanes and gliders) achieve airflow past the wings by having the entire aircraft moving forward through the air, while rotorcraft (helicopters and autogyros) do so by having mobile, elongated wings spinning rapidly around a mast in an assembly known as the rotor.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Gliders were one of the first forms of a fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] They are a special type of aircraft that doesn't require an engine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The first person to successfully build a human-carrying glider was George Cayley, who also was the first to discover the four major aerodynamic forces.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The first powered aircraft (Airplane) was invented by Wilbur and Orville Wright.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] A *rotary-wing aircraft*, *rotorwing aircraft* or *rotorcraft* is a heavier-than-air aircraft with rotary wings that spin around a vertical mast to generate lift.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The assembly of several rotor blades mounted on a single mast is referred to as a rotor.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) defines a rotorcraft as "supported in flight by the reactions of the air on one or more rotors".
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Rotorcraft generally include aircraft where one or more rotors provide lift throughout the entire flight, such as helicopters, gyroplanes, autogyros, and gyrodynes.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Compound rotorcraft augment the rotor with additional thrust engines, propellers, or static lifting surfaces.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Some types, such as helicopters, are capable of vertical takeoff and landing.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] An aircraft that uses rotor lift for vertical flight but changes to solely fixed-wing lift in horizontal flight is not a rotorcraft but a convertiplane.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The largest aircraft by weight and largest regular fixed-wing aircraft ever built, as of 2016, was the Antonov An-225 *Mriya*.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] That Soviet-built (Ukrainian SSR) six-engine transport of the 1980s was 84 m (276 ft) long, with an 88 m (289 ft) wingspan.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] It holds the world payload record, after transporting 428,834 lb (194,516 kg) of goods, and has flown 100 t (220,000 lb) loads commercially.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] With a maximum loaded weight of 550–700 t (1,210,000–1,540,000 lb), it was also the heaviest aircraft built to date.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The aircraft was destroyed during the Russo-Ukrainian War.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The largest military airplanes are the Ukrainian Antonov An-124 *Ruslan* (world's second-largest airplane, also used as a civilian transport), and American Lockheed C-5 Galaxy transport, weighing, loaded, over 380 t (840,000 lb).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The fastest recorded powered aircraft flight and fastest recorded aircraft flight of an air-breathing powered aircraft was of the NASA X-43A *Pegasus*, a scramjet-powered, hypersonic, lifting body experimental research aircraft, at Mach 9.68 or 6,755 mph (10,870 km/h) on 16 November 2004.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Before the X-43A, the fastest recorded powered airplane flight, and still the record for the fastest manned powered airplane, was the North American X-15, rocket-powered airplane at Mach 6.7 or 7,274 km/h (4,520 mph) on 3 October 1967.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The fastest manned, air-breathing powered airplane is the Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird, a U.S. reconnaissance jet fixed-wing aircraft, having reached 3,530 km/h (2,193 mph) on 28 July 1976.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The main feature of unpowered aircraft is the inability to directly provide thrust through its engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] This means that all unpowered aircraft rely on the environment for sustained flight.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Gliders, for example, take advantage of their aerodynamic properties to enable them to travel long distances.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Techniques such as thermal circling, where gliders fly into warm air which allows them to rise, prolong flight time.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Due to the lack of an engine, initial propulsion assistance is usually necessary to ensure flight.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] A common glider launching method is aerotowing, where another aircraft tows the glider to an altitude from which sustained flight is possible.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Steering for a glider is also rudimentary, while more complex gliders like sailplanes usually have joysticks for steering, more basic aircraft like hang gliders rely on the pilot's physical coordination to change the centre of gravity.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] A powered aircraft is an aircraft with a source of mechanical power, used to produce thrust.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Such sources are generally engines, as is the case with airplanes, but can be human-powered in more extreme cases.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Propeller aircraft, as their name suggests, rely on propellers to produce thrust for the airplane.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Compared to engines using propellers, jet engines can provide much higher thrust, higher speeds and, above about 40,000 ft (12,000 m), greater efficiency.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Although some rotorcraft, such as rotor kites, can be unpowered, most rotorcraft are powered by either piston engines or turboprops.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Some rotorcraft, including autogyros and gyrodynes, are propelled by a conventional propeller or jet engine, with the rotor unpowered, but most modern rotorcraft have a powered rotor, allowing them to hover in place.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Autogyros and gyrodynes are steered using a rudder, similarly to propeller and jet aircraft, and rotorcraft with powered rotors, such as helicopters, turn by adjusting the pitch of the rotor cyclically, so that the rotors on one side produce more lift than the other.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Rotorcraft with powered rotors typically need a tail rotor to counter the rotational torque produced by the rotor, which can cause the helicopter to spin.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] An *aerostat* or *lighter-than-air aircraft* relies on buoyancy to maintain flight.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Aerostats include unpowered balloons (free-flying or tethered) and powered airships.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The relative density of an aerostat as a whole is lower than that of the surrounding atmospheric air (hence the name "lighter-than-air").
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Its main component is one or more gas capsules made of lightweight skins, containing a lifting gas (hot air, or any gas with lower density than air, typically hydrogen or helium) that displaces a large volume of air to generate enough buoyancy to overcome its own weight.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Payload (passengers and cargo) can then be carried on attached components such as a basket, a gondola, a cabin or various hardpoints.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] With airships, which need to be able to fly against wind, the lifting gas capsules are often protected by a more rigid outer envelope or an airframe, with other gasbags such as ballonets to help modulate buoyancy.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Aerostats are so named because they use aerostatic buoyant force that does not require any forward movement through the surrounding air mass, resulting in the inherent ability to levitate and perform vertical takeoff and landing.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] This contrasts with the heavier-than-air aerodynes that primarily use aerodynamic lift, which must have consistent airflow over an aerofoil (wing) surface to stay airborne.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The term has also been used in a narrower sense, to refer to the statically tethered balloon in contrast to the free-flying airship.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] This article uses the term in its broader sense.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] An *aerodyne* is a heavier-than-air aircraft that relies on aerodynamic lift, or upthrust produced by the airflow, to fly.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Aerodynes include rotorcraft, airplanes, gliders, and several other varieties of aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Airplanes use wings, or airfoils, to direct the airflow to produce lift.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Wings are usually constructed with a wooden or metal inner framework, and a skin stretched over it.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Rotorcraft use a rotor which acts like a rotating wing, allowing them to hover in place.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] When aerodynes carry a payload, it is usually carried inside the aircraft's fuselage, or central structure, but aerodynes can also carry loads attached outside the aircraft or inside the wing.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Unlike aerostats, which control their altitude by changing their weight, aerodynes use control surfaces to control their altitude, or raise or lower the lift on their wing by adjusting their speed.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] As they typically travel at higher speeds than aerostats, most aerodynes have a rigid structure consisting of a frame covered by a skin.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Powered aircraft are typically powered by internal combustion engines (piston or turbine) burning fossil fuels—typically gasoline (avgas) or jet fuel.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] A very few are powered by rocket power, ramjet propulsion, or by electric motors, or by internal combustion engines of other types, or using other fuels.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] A very few have been powered, for short flights, by human muscle energy (e.g.: Gossamer Condor).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The avionics comprise any *electronic* aircraft flight control systems and related equipment, including electronic cockpit instrumentation, navigation, radar, monitoring, and communications systems.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The flight envelope of an aircraft refers to its approved design capabilities in terms of airspeed, load factor and altitude.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The maximal total *range* is the maximum distance an aircraft can fly between takeoff and landing.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Powered aircraft range is limited by the aviation fuel energy storage capacity (chemical or electrical) considering both weight and volume limits.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Unpowered aircraft range depends on factors such as cross-country speed and environmental conditions.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The range can be seen as the cross-country ground speed multiplied by the maximum time in the air.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The fuel time limit for powered aircraft is fixed by the available fuel (considering reserve fuel requirements) and the rate of consumption.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The Airbus A350-900ULR is among the longest range airliners.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Some aircraft can gain energy while airborne through the environment (e.g. collecting solar energy or through rising air currents from mechanical or thermal lifting) or from in-flight refueling.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] These aircraft could theoretically have an infinite range.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Control systems adjust the orientation of a vehicle about its CG.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] A control system includes control surfaces which, when deflected, generate a moment (or couple from ailerons) about the cg which rotates the aircraft in pitch, roll, and yaw.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] For example, a pitching moment comes from a force applied at a distance forward or aft of the cg, causing the aircraft to pitch up or down.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] A fixed-wing aircraft increases or decreases the lift generated by the wings when it pitches nose up or down by increasing or decreasing the angle of attack (AOA).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The roll angle is also known as bank angle on a fixed-wing aircraft, which usually "banks" to change the horizontal direction of flight.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] A fixed wing is typically unstable in pitch, roll, and yaw.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Pitch and yaw stabilities of conventional fixed wing designs require horizontal and vertical stabilisers, which act similarly to the feathers on an arrow.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] These stabilizing surfaces allow equilibrium of aerodynamic forces and to stabilise the flight dynamics of pitch and yaw.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In fixed-wing aircraft, multiple control surfaces are used to adjust the aircraft's roll, pitch, and yaw.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Ailerons, hinged surfaces normally located on the rear edge of the wing, can raise or lower the lift produced by one side of the wing, causing the aircraft to bank to one side.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Elevators, usually located in the horizontal stabilizer, are used to increase or decrease the lift produced by the tail, causing the aircraft to pitch upwards or downwards, which in turn affects the lift of the wing.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] However, when the ailerons are used to turn an aircraft to the left, the right aileron must be tilted downwards, producing more drag than the left aileron and causing the aircraft to yaw right.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] To counteract this force, most fixed-wing aircraft have a rudder mounted on the vertical stabilizer which can deflect the airflow to the tail left or right to control the aircraft's yaw.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In rotorcraft, control is mainly accomplished through the cyclical tilting of the rotor's blades, increasing the angle of attack of the blades on one side and decreasing the angle of attack on the other.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Similarly to the rudder on fixed-wing aircraft, rotorcraft with powered rotors have a tail rotor, which counters the rotational thrust produced by the rotor and allows the aircraft to turn in forward flight.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Rotorcraft with unpowered rotors, such as autogyros, use a rudder for yaw.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Aircraft engines produce gases, noise, and particulates from fossil fuel combustion, raising environmental concerns over their global effects and on local air quality.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Jet airliners contribute to climate change by emitting carbon dioxide (CO2), the best understood greenhouse gas, and, with less scientific understanding, nitrogen oxides, contrails and particulates.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Their radiative forcing is estimated at 1.4 that of CO2 alone, excluding induced cirrus cloud with a very low level of scientific understanding.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In 2018, global commercial operations generated 2.4% of CO2 emissions.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Jet airliners have become more fuel efficient and CO2 emissions per revenue ton-kilometer (RTK) in 2018 were 47% of those in 1990.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In 2018, CO2 emissions averaged 88 grams of CO2 per revenue passenger per km.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] While the aviation industry is more fuel efficient, overall emissions have risen as the volume of air travel has increased.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] By 2020, aviation emissions were 70% higher than in 2005 and they could grow by 300% by 2050.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Aircraft noise pollution disrupts sleep, children's education and could increase cardiovascular risk.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Airports can generate water pollution due to their extensive handling of jet fuel and deicing chemicals if not contained, contaminating nearby water bodies.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Aviation activities emit ozone and ultrafine particles, both of which are health hazards.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Piston engines used in general aviation burn Avgas, releasing toxic lead.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Aviation's environmental footprint can be reduced by better fuel economy in aircraft, or air traffic control and flight routes can be optimized to lower non-CO2 effects on climate from NOx, particulates or contrails.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Aviation biofuel, emissions trading and carbon offsetting, part of the ICAO's CORSIA, can lower CO2 emissions.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Aviation usage can be lowered by short-haul flight bans, train connections, personal choices and aviation taxation and subsidies.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Fuel-powered aircraft may be replaced by hybrid electric aircraft and electric aircraft or by hydrogen-powered aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Since 2021, the IATA members plan to achieve net-zero carbon emissions by 2050, followed by the ICAO in 2022.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] A military aircraft is any aircraft that is operated by a legal or insurrectionary armed service of any type.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Although scheduled air transport is the larger operation in terms of passenger numbers, GA is larger in the number of flights (and flight hours, in the U.S.) In the U.S., GA carries 166 million passengers each year, more than any individual airline, though less than all the airlines combined.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Since 2004, the U.S. airlines combined have carried over 600 million passengers each year, and in 2014, they carried a combined 662,819,232 passengers.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] All scheduled air transport is commercial, but general aviation can be either commercial or private.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Normally, the pilot, aircraft, and operator must all be authorized to perform commercial operations through separate commercial licensing, registration, and operation certificates.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] An *experimental aircraft* is an aircraft intended for testing new aerospace technologies and design concepts.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The term *research aircraft* or *testbed aircraft*, by contrast, generally denotes aircraft modified to perform scientific studies, such as weather research or geophysical surveying, similar to a research vessel.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] The term "experimental aircraft" also has specific legal meaning in Australia, the United States and some other countries; usually used to refer to aircraft flown with an experimental certificate.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] In the United States, this also includes most homebuilt aircraft, many of which are based on conventional designs and hence are experimental only in name because of certain restrictions in operation.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Model aircraft are typically small-scale replicas of flying aircraft, or new designs built smaller than most passenger aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Static model aircraft, which cannot fly, are usually not considered to be aircraft, but they can be used to test aspects of a flying aircraft, such as its aerodynamics.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Flying models are commonly propelled by electric motors, combustion engines, or are gliders, but there are many alternate methods of propulsion, such as wound rubber bands and small jet engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/aircraft] Most flying model aircraft are either radio-controlled aircraft, fly freely, or are controlled by wires held by the pilot.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The history of the capacitor discharge ignition system can be traced back to the 1890s when it is believed that Nikola Tesla was the first to propose such an ignition system.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Originally invented for Henry Fords six cylinder racer in 1905, the first production use of a CDI system was put into use in 1906 as standard equipment with the Ford Model K.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The Model K utilized dual ignition systems, one of which was the Holley-Huff Magneto, or Huff System, manufactured by the Holley Brothers Company.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Huff with US patent #882003 filed July 1, 1905 and assigned to Henry Ford.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The system used an engine driven DC generator that charged a capacitor and then discharged the capacitor through the ignition coil primary winding.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] It was the Robert Bosch company which was the pioneer of the first electronic CD ignitions.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] (Bosch is also responsible for the invention of the high-tension magneto.) During World War Two, Bosch had fitted thyratron (tube type) CD ignitions to some piston engined fighter aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] With a CD ignition, an aeroplane engine did not need a warm up period for reliable ignition and so a fighter aircraft could take flight more quickly as a result.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] This early German system used a rotary DC converter along with fragile tube circuitry, and was not suited to life in a fighter aircraft.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Failures occurred within only a few hours.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The quest for a reliable electronic means of producing a CD ignition began in earnest during the 1950s.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] In the mid-1950s, the Engineering Research Institute of the University of Michigan in cooperation with Chrysler Corporation in the United States worked to find a method to produce a viable solution.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] They were unsuccessful, but did provide much data on the advantages of such a system, should one be built.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Namely; a fast voltage rise time to fire fouled or wet spark plugs, high energy throughout the RPM range resulting in better starting, more power and economy, and lower emissions.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] A few engineers, scientists, and hobbyists had built CD ignitions throughout the 1950s using thyratrons.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] However, thyratrons were unsuitable for use in automobiles for two reasons.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] They required a warm-up period which was a nuisance, and were vulnerable to vibration which drastically reduced their service life.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] In an automotive application, the thyratron CD ignition would fail in weeks or months.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The unreliability of those early thyratron CD ignitions made them unsuitable for mass production despite providing short term benefits.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] One company at least, Tung-Sol (a manufacturer of vacuum tubes) marketed a thyratron CD ignition, model Tung-Sol EI-4 in 1962, but it was expensive.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Despite the failings of thyratron CD ignitions, the improved ignition that they gave made them a worthwhile addition for some drivers.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] For the Wankel powered NSU Spider of 1964, Bosch resurrected its thyratron method for a CD ignition and used this up until at least 1966.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] It suffered the same reliability problems as the Tung-Sol EI-4.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] It was the SCR, Silicon-controlled rectifier or thyristor invented in the late 1950s that replaced the troublesome thyratron, and paved the way for a reliable solid-state CD ignition.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] This was thanks to Bill Gutzwiller and his team at General Electric.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The SCR was rugged with an indefinite lifetime, but very prone to unwanted trigger impulses which would turn the SCR 'on'.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Unwanted trigger impulses in early attempts at using SCRs for CD ignitions were caused by electrical interference, but the main culprit proved to be 'points bounce'.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Points bounce is a feature of a points-triggered system.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] In the standard system with points, distributor, ignition coil, ignition (Kettering system) points bounce prevents the coil from saturating fully as RPM increases resulting in a weak spark, thus limiting high speed potential.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] In a CD ignition, at least those early attempts, the points bounce created unwanted trigger pulses to the SCR (thyristor) that resulted in a series of weak, untimed sparks that caused extreme misfiring.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] There were two possible solutions to the problem.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The first would be to develop another means of triggering the discharge of the capacitor to one discharge per power stroke by replacing the points with something else.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] This could be done magnetically or optically, but that would necessitate more electronics and an expensive distributor.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The other option was to keep the points, as they were already in use and reliable, and find a way to overcome the 'points bounce' problem.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] This was accomplished in April 1962 by a Canadian, RCAF officer F.L.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Winterburn working in his basement in Ottawa, Ontario.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The design used an inexpensive method that would recognize only the first opening of the points and ignore subsequent openings when the points bounced.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] A company was formed in Ottawa in early 1963 called Hyland Electronics building CD ignitions using the Winterburn design.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The discharge capacitor within the CD ignition had the ability to provide a powerful spark in excess of 4 times the spark power of the Kettering system using the same coil, with the exception that spark energy could be maintained at high rpm unlike the Kettering system.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The Hyland unit consumed only four amperes at 5000rpm (8cyl) or 10,000rpm(4cyl).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Dynamometer testing during 1963 and 1964 showed a minimum of 5% increase in horsepower with the system, with 10% the norm.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] One example, a Ford Falcon, had an increase in horsepower of 17%.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Spark plug lifespan was increased to at least 50,000 miles and points lifespan was greatly extended from 8,000 miles to at least 60,000 miles.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Points lifespan became a factor of rubbing block (cam follower) wear and the life cycle of the spring with some lasting almost 100,000 miles.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The Hyland unit was tolerant of varied points gaps.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The system could be switched back to standard inductive discharge ignition by the swapping of two wires.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The Hyland CD ignition was the first commercially produced solid-state CD ignition and retailed for $39.95 Canadian.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The patents were applied for by Winterburn on September 23, 1963 (United States patent# 3,564,581).
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The design was leaked to the United States in the summer of 1963 when Hyland exposed the design to a US company in an effort to expand sales.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Afterward, numerous companies started building their own throughout the 1960s and 1970s without licence.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Some were direct copies of the Winterburn circuit.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] In 1971 Bosch bought the European patent rights (German, French, British) from Winterburn.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The UK Wireless World magazine of January 1970 published a detailed Capacitor-discharge Ignition system as an electronic hobby build project by R.M.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The circuit of this system was similar to the Winterburn patent in that it used a push-pull converted switch mode oscillator for energy transfer to a store - discharge capacitor and conventional contact breakers to initiate a thyristor triggering discharge of the charged CD capacitor.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] It was stated to offer several advantages over conventional ignition.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Among which: better combustion, easy starting even under subzero conditions, immunity to contactor (points) bounce and 2% - 5% fuel economy.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Subsequent letters to Wireless World ( March & May 1970), with Mr.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Marston's replies, further discussed aspects of the design and build.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Harris, undergraduate of the City University London made a detailed electrical engineering analysis of the Marston design as well as automotive engine measurement trials to verify fuel economy.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] These confirmed the benefits of the CD ignition system.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] However, he found that the core ingredient of the CD design rested on careful hand winding of the switch mode transformer and appropriate selection of oscillator transistors and choice of oscillator frequency.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] In a CDI system, a charging circuit charges a high voltage capacitor, and at the instant of ignition, usually determined by a crank position sensor, the system stops charging the capacitor, allowing the capacitor to discharge its output to the ignition coil before reaching the spark plug.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] A typical CDI module consists of a small transformer, a charging circuit, a triggering circuit and a main capacitor.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] First, the system voltage is raised to 250 to 600 volts by a power supply inside the CDI module.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Then, the electric current flows to the charging circuit and charges the capacitor.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The rectifier inside the charging circuit prevents capacitor discharge before the moment of ignition.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] When the triggering circuit receives the triggering signal, the triggering circuit stops the operation of the charging circuit, allowing the capacitor to discharge its output rapidly to the low inductance ignition coil.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] In a CD ignition, the ignition coil acts as a pulse transformer rather than an energy storage medium as it does in an inductive system.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The voltage output to the spark plugs is highly dependent on the design of the CD ignition.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Voltages exceeding the insulation capabilities of existing ignition components can lead to early failure of those components.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Most CD ignitions are made to give very high output voltages but this is not always beneficial.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] When there is no triggering signal the charging circuit is re-connected to charge the capacitor.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The amount of energy the CDI system can store for the generation of a spark is dependent on the voltage and capacitance of the capacitors used, but usually it is around 50 mJ, or more.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The standard points/coil/distributor ignition, more properly called the inductive discharge ignition system or Kettering ignition system, produces 25mJ at low speed and drops off quickly as speed increases.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] One factor often not taken into consideration when discussing CDI spark energy is the actual energy provided to the spark gap versus the energy applied to the primary side of the coil.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] As a simple example, a typical ignition coil may have a secondary winding resistance of 4000 ohms and a secondary current of 400 milliamperes.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Once a spark has struck, the voltage across the spark gap in a running engine drops to a relatively low value, in the order of 1500-2000 volts.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] This, combined with the fact that the coil secondary current of 400 milliamperes loses approximately 1600 volts through the 4000 ohm secondary resistance means that fully 50% of the energy is lost in heating the coil secondary.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Actual measurements show the real world efficiency to be only 35 to 38% when coil primary winding losses are included.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The AC-CDI module obtains its electricity source solely from the alternating current produced by the alternator.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The AC-CDI system is the most basic CDI system which is widely used in small engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The DC-CDI module is powered by the battery, and therefore an additional DC/AC inverter circuit is included in the CDI module to raise the 12 V DC to 400-600 V DC, making the CDI module slightly larger.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] However, vehicles that use DC-CDI systems have more precise ignition timing and the engine can be started more easily when cold.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Not all small engine ignition systems are CDI.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Some engines like older Briggs and Stratton use magneto ignition.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The entire ignition system, coil and points, are under the magnetized flywheel.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Another sort of ignition system commonly used on small off-road motorcycles in the 1960s and 1970s was called Energy Transfer.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] A coil under the flywheel generated a strong DC current pulse as the flywheel magnet moved over it.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] (If the engine was rotated while examining the wave-form output of the coil with an oscilloscope, it would appear to be AC.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] However, since the charge-time of the coil corresponds to much less than a full revolution of the crank, the coil really 'sees' only DC current for charging the external ignition coil.) This DC current flowed through a wire to an ignition coil mounted outside of the engine.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The points sometimes were under the flywheel for two-stroke engines, and commonly on the camshaft for four-stroke engines.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] This system worked like all Kettering (points/coil) ignition systems: the opening points trigger the collapse of the magnetic field in the ignition coil, producing a high voltage pulse which flows through the spark plug wire to the spark plug.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Some electronic ignition systems exist that are not CDI.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] These systems use a transistor to switch the charging current to the coil off and on at the appropriate times.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] This eliminates the problem of burned and worn points, and provides a hotter spark because of the faster voltage rise and collapse time in the ignition coil.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] A CDI system has a short charging time, a fast voltage rise (between 3 ~ 10 kV/μs) compared to typical inductive systems (300 ~ 500 V/μs) and a short spark duration limited to about 50-600 μs.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The fast voltage rise makes CDI systems insensitive to shunt resistance, but the limited spark duration can for some applications be too short to provide reliable ignition.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The insensitivity to shunt resistance and the ability to fire multiple sparks can provide improved cold starting ability.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] Since the CDI system provides only a reduced duration spark, it's also possible to combine this ignition system with ionization measurement.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] This is done by connecting a low voltage (about 80 V) to the spark plug, except when fired.
[src:capacitor-discharge-ignition/capacitor-discharge-ignition] The current flow over the spark plug can then be used to calculate the temperature and pressure inside the cylinder.
